        "response": "## Relevant Problems:\n\nQ: Jamie has two loans. The first loan has an interest rate of 6% per year, and the second loan has an interest rate of 8% per year. Jamie owes $2000 more on the second loan than the first. Last year, Jamie paid a total of $480 in interest. The total amount Jamie owes on both loans is $7000. How much does Jamie owe on each loan?\nA: Let x be the amount Jamie owes on the first loan. Then the second loan amount is x + $2000. The total interest paid is 0.06x + 0.08(x + $2000) = $480. The total amount owed is x + (x + $2000) = $7000. Solving these equations simultaneously gives x = $2500 for the first loan and x + $2000 = $4500 for the second loan. The amounts Jamie owes on each loan are \\boxed{$2500} and \\boxed{$4500}.\n\nQ: Alex has three different debts with interest rates of 4%, 6%, and 8% per year. He owes $1000 more on the debt with the highest interest rate than the one with the lowest interest rate. Last year, he paid a total of $620 in interest. The total amount he owes is $8000. How much does he owe for each debt?\nA: Let the amount owed on the debt with the lowest interest rate be x. Then the amount owed on the highest interest rate debt is x + $1000. Let y be the amount owed on the debt with the middle interest rate. The total interest paid is 0.04x + 0.06y + 0.08(x + $1000) = $620. The total amount owed is x + y + (x + $1000) = $8000. Solving these equations gives x = $2000, y = $3000, and x + $1000 = $3000. The amounts Alex owes on each debt are \\boxed{$2000}, \\boxed{$3000}, and \\boxed{$3000}.\n\nQ: Taylor has two credit card debts. The first card has an interest rate of 10% per year, and the second card has an interest rate of 15% per year. Taylor owes $500 more on the second card than the first. Last year, Taylor paid a total of $600 in interest. The total amount Taylor owes on both cards is $4000. How much does Taylor owe on each card?\nA: Let x be the amount Taylor owes on the first card. Then the second card amount is x + $500. The total interest paid is 0.10x + 0.15(x + $500) = $600. The total amount owed is x + (x + $500) = $4000. Solving these equations simultaneously gives x = $1500 for the first card and x + $500 = $2000 for the second card. The amounts Taylor owes on each card are \\boxed{$1500} and \\boxed{$2000}.\n\n## Solve the Initial Problem:\nLet's solve the following math problem.\n\nQ: Hollis is paying off three student loans. The first loan charges 7% interest per year, the second loan charges 9% interest per year, and the third loan charges 5% interest per year. He owes $1500 more on the first loan than he does on the second loan. Last year, he paid a total of $717 in interest. The total amount he owes on all three loans is $9900. How much does he owe on each loan?\nA: Let x be the amount Hollis owes on the second loan. Then the first loan amount is x + $1500. Let y be the amount owed on the third loan. The total interest paid is 0.07(x + $1500) + 0.09x + 0.05y = $717. The total amount owed is (x + $1500) + x + y = $9900. We have two equations:\n\n1) 0.07(x + $1500) + 0.09x + 0.05y = $717\n2) x + $1500 + x + y = $9900\n\nSimplifying the first equation by distributing the interest rates:\n\n0.07x + $105 + 0.09x + 0.05y = $717\n0.16x + 0.05y = $612\n\nSimplifying the second equation:\n\n2x + y = $8400\n\nNow we have a system of two equations with two variables:\n\n0.16x + 0.05y = $612\n2x + y = $8400\n\nTo solve this system, we can multiply the first equation by 20 to eliminate y:\n\n3.2x + y = $12240\n\nNow subtract the second equation from this result:\n\n3.2x + y - (2x + y) = $12240 - $8400\n1.2x = $3840\nx = $3200\n\nNow we can find y by substituting x back into the second equation:\n\n2($3200) + y = $8400\n$6400 + y = $8400\ny = $8400 - $6400\ny = $2000\n\nFinally, we can find the amount for the first loan:\n\nx + $1500 = $3200 + $1500\n= $4700\n\nThe amounts Hollis owes on each loan are \\boxed{$4700}, \\boxed{$3200}, and \\boxed{$2000}."
